My Favorite Unfiltered Memories of 2022 
 
This was the most emotional year of my life & also the most important year of my life. When I left my family, friends, stable job and pretty much everything I knew, I started the honeymoon phase of van life. So really, I avoided "feelings" for the first year. 
 
Fast forward to this year, I was LOST. I started 2022 sprinting in the van from Colorado to Arizona to Utah to Colorado to California and back all in 2 months and I was BURNT OUT. But I realized I was just running away from myself and the emotions I have been too scared to process.
 
This was also the most important year of my life because I finally am accepting, processing and moving forward with these emotions I've been running from, but also because I am one step closer to me after constantly asking myself WHY. Why am I doing this? What purpose does this serve? Do I even like this? 
 
These question have pushed me into doing things I never in a million years thought I would be doing-- like having wine on top of a mountain I just backpacked to with internet friends or working with The North Face, Bank of America and T-Mobile, or hosting a trip to Bali with 26 people! Like WHAT I am so lucky & grateful for those that have helped me create this life. 
 
That being said, I am so excited to head into this new year feeling a lot less lost and I think there is this combined feeling that 2023 IS OUR YEAR. Truly. The energy going into this new year is unmatched & I am so excited to see what we all do. Happy new year friends! Love y'all so much.

Please pray for Otto. After countless vet visits & bloodwork, unfortunately Otto has been diagnosed with FIP after showing signs of severe weight loss. 

I’m absolutely heartbroken over my sweet, 3.5 year old lil dude. Atlas and Otto came into my life together as brothers in late 2019 and they are the best things to ever happen to me. I love them so much and would do anything for them. 

Next steps:
Today I’ll be making a 7 hour drive to Colorado State University (per so many of your and vet suggestions), to hopefully get some additional tests done. 

I have joined the FB group with access to a possible cure & I’ve received incredible dms of those who’s lives its saved, and I’m hopeful. 🙏🏻

Otto doesn’t have any interest in food. So if you have any ideas on how to encourage him to eat, please comment. 

I’m so scared, anxious, panicked but remain hopeful 💖 Any info or support you have, would mean the absolute world. 

I’m praying to see otto have the van zoomies with his brother in no time 💖

Love y’all so much.

Otto Update: I'm devastated to be writing that my sweet, darling boy has terminal cancer. Over the last two days, the amazing doctors at Colorado State University ran test after test on Otto to confirm the original FIP diagnosis (and to determine if he was healthy enough to treat with the blk mrk meds). It was still appearing that way until new fluid in his lungs was tested. The tests came back for an extremely rare (for his 3 year old age) cancer called Carcinomatosis aka a very aggressive, terminal cancer. They estimate that my darling boy only has a few days to a few weeks left. There is no treatment. 
 
I'm in shock. True shock. I don’t know how to process this. I feel like I am in a nightmare and can't wake up.
 
Right now, I am back at my dad's house with Atlas and I will try to make his life as comfortable and joyful as possible until it's his time. 
 
For 3.5 years old, he lived the absolute greatest life a cat could have-- from hiking up mountains in Washington & Idaho, to climbing the boulders of Moab, to exploring the waterfalls of Oregon to growing up in a van & on a peach farm in Colorado. I am so grateful he got to experience so much. I am so grateful for the purpose and love he gave me. 
 
Otto, I love you more than life itself. 
 
I will miss the way you pet my shoulder to get under the covers. I will miss you sitting in my lap on roadtrips. I will miss your peach tree climbs & rim trail hikes. I will miss you protecting your brother from dogs. I will miss the play fights you and atlas have while on our morning walks or when you try to scare him through the bushes. I will miss looking for you in the blackberry bushes. I will miss your kind eyes & tiger stripes. Most of all, I will just miss you. You and your brother are the greatest thing to ever happen to me.

Rest in paradise sweet Otto 🕊
 
Many said you’ll know when it’s their time and on Thursday, Otto had let me know it was time after his breathing had increased to an extremely uncomfortable level due to cancer. So, someone came to the house to help him pass and it was a beautiful ceremony. 
 
I have no words other than, thank you Otto. Thank you for coming into my life at the time I needed you most and giving me so much purpose. 
 
Your brother and I love you so much. I just know you are watching over us dangling from a peach tree right now. 

Otto

Van life seems weird to imagine you not in it, meowing to go outside to climb rocks, but I am forever grateful for the millions of memories and my addiction to recording them. So while I can't look at my entire camera roll quite yet to find my absolute favorite captured moments, here are some pretty perfect ones.

I made sure to have otto's bed, favorite sweatshirt and blanket all out so Atlas could still smell him. What's next for me… Atlas and I will move back into the van this week and continue on our adventure. Tbh, I feel a bit guilty for just going back to normal life, but I know that’s what has to happen.

TW: Mental Health, Intrusive Thoughts & Dissociation. This post is scary for me to share because being vulnerable is terrifying, but let’s try👇🏻

After everything that’s happened over the last few months, I find myself slipping into some old patterns. 
 
I started seeing a therapist five years ago because I didn’t believe I existed. I was so internally checked out due to stress (among other things), that I didn’t feel anything. 
 
After the intrusive thoughts started, I knew I needed to see someone. I searched for therapists in my area and went to two others before I found my person. After sharing my story, I learned that this was my brain’s way of protecting me. My therapist told me what I was feeling was called Dissociation and Call of the Void (the scary thoughts) and that it was actually incredibly common. 
 
Note: If you don’t mesh well with the first/second therapist, try another. 
 
Obviously I didn’t want these feelings/thoughts anymore, so I began practicing different methods on how to bring myself back to being me. The ones that worked best for me were: 
	•	Dipping my head in a bowl of ice water
	•	Meditating (I am SO bad at sticking with this routine, but it really does help)
	•	Counting the colors. I will try to find every shade of green (etc) around me. 
	•	Journaling 
	•	Greeting the emotions, accepting them and knowing they are temporary and will pass. 
 
Now, healing is not linear & it’s different for everyone. And not everyone is going to understand your healing journey. Read that again. Not everyone will be supportive of the work your doing. But this is YOUR WORK for YOURSELF. 
 
Sharing this is scary to me, but even if it helps one person, it’s worth it. I love y’all. Thank you for allowing me to be so vulnerable. 
 
You are not alone.  
 
Note: I recognize my privilege for being able to have a therapist. I hope that a few of the coping mechanisms and terms I shared today are helpful in anyone else’s journey who may not be able to see a therapist.

Solo Van Life w/ Cats: Why I Don’t Have AC👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻
 
After 2+ years on the road, here is what I recommend doing when you have pets and no AC. *Y’all know this, but I would NEVER put my cats in any danger. Their safety is my number one concern.* 
 
	•	Have at least 2 forms of air circulation in your van! I have 2 Maxxair fans that blow in and out and 2 windows. When the fans are turned on, it creates an amazing wind tunnel. 
 
	•	Have a pocket/partition door that separates the hottest part of the vehicle from the living space. You can also use an insulated & weighted curtain!  
	•	FULLY INSULATE your van! My van is fully insulated and not like a regular vehicle. 
 
	•	Invest in heavy duty window covers! I get mine from @vanmadegear and LOVE them! I travel for 85 degrees and below and spend most of my summer in the mountains. 
 
	•	Get a hotel if there is a heat wave! 
 
Other Notes: 
	•	Make sure they have plenty of water! 
	•	Put cold/wet towels on the ground for them to lay on. 
	•	Have a camera to monitor them while you are running errands. I connect my @ring camera to my portable wifi jetpack from @verizon 
	•	LEAVE YOUR CONTACT INFO ON YOUR DASH! Many don’t know your cats are totally fine and will try to help them.

The reason I chose to not have AC is because it takes too much power and I really don’t think I personally need it.
 
HOWEVER: If you have to stay somewhere that is HOT all summer and you have a place to plug your van in THEN I absolutely recommend getting AC!

Am I getting another cat?👇🏻
 
It's been almost 4 months since my sweet Otto passed, so here's an update about where Atlas and I are at: 
 
How is Atlas doing? 
• Atlas has been himself, while at the same time a completely different cat. Prior to Otto's death, Atlas never cuddled ONCE with me. Not once. He was so friendly and sweet, but always just focused on cuddling with his brother. That has COMPLETELY CHANGED. He sleeps next to me every night and craves any bit of attention.  Recently, I went back to my builder's shop (where the boys had spent a lot of time) and Atlas looked for Otto there. It was heartbreaking. I can tell he still misses his brother so much. But overall, Atlas is still being his goofy, friendly self and eating (a lot). 
 
How Am I Doing? 
• Over the last 4 months, we have gone to Otto's favorite places: Moab, my dad's & Bend. Each of those places has helped me heal and I'll forever remember the cute lil memories we all shared there. Now, the grief comes in waves (as it does). Otto was involved in every aspect of my life on the road for three years. Somedays I catch myself forgetting small moments like what his meow sounded like, but then I remember I recorded everything. Now mentally, I have run into a bit of a negativity patch. (I’m working on it w/ my therapist). I have just been feeling meh & I have been struggling w/ finding joy. Example: I used to take such joy in sharing my adventures of both of them but recently, it just feels different. I love my adventures with Atlas and of course I will keep posting (because also I love & appreciate how much joy it brings you, looking at comments makes my heart heal so much), but it's hard. Overall, I am proud for allowing myself to feel & honor all of the emotions. 
 
SO, am I getting another cat? 
• Short answer, yes. I'm manifesting that Otto will send one directly to my van's door and in the morning when I let Atlas out, a sweet little kitten will be waiting for us. BUT in case that doesn't happen, in the next six months (ISH), I will be getting a friend for Atlas. 
 
I love & appreciate you all so much and my heart goes out to anyone who has ever lost 🫶

Van Life, Cats & Crossing Foreign Borders: here’s what you need to know 👇🏻

Atlas and I are OFFICIALLY IN CANADA!! This is our first  foreign country in the van together! Atlas is officially Mr. Worldwide! 🇨🇦

We crossed at the Chief Mountain Port of Entry right outside of Glacier National Park because it is one of the lease crowded customs points. Which I can confirm it was. 

Here is what I did to prepare the van & my cat for the border crossing: 

Pets: if you have pets and you want to bring them to Canada you MUST make sure they are up to date on their rabies sho ts. Bring all of their paperwork in case you get asked. I personally didn’t get asked if I had a pet. 

Remove/Re-home Illegal Items: safety items (pepper spray, tasers and the other one), any live bait or animal/fish/fruits & veggies and those questionable substances. 

Clean your passenger seat: now this could just be a rumor, but I’ve heard if you look like you have a TON of stuff, it could be sus. So I cleaned everything out of my main cab (which I should do anyway for safety reasons haha) 

Don’t forget your passport! 

Lmk if you have any questions!

5 Reasons I’ve ALMOST QUIT van life👇🏻

Let’s be clear, the pros definitely outweigh the cons BUT… I wanted to talk about why I’ve almost quit multiple times. 

1. Everything breaks. I’ve talked about this before, but whether it’s a drawer, cabinets falling, heater or fridge not working… it’s just inconvenient when you live in 60 square feet and depend on those items. Yes, things break in homes/apartments often too but this just hits different. 

2. You won’t ever really have a “relaxing” day. You have to do your basic human tasks like empty your pee tank, find sun for your solar power, find a place to sleep… and it just weighs on you. In a house, most of these things are just built in and you never think about them. 

3. Safety. I’ve gotten knocked on 5 times this year by the police in the middle of the night and I’m truthfully scarred from it. Your guard is always up because you’re constantly doing things to make sure you’re safe- sending cords, wearing baggy clothes on drive days, sleeping next to safety items etc

4. Family and friends. When Otto was sick, I wanted nothing more than to be surrounded by my friends and family. I’m grateful to have my dad with me when it happened, but I missed calling my best friends to just be there in person for me. I also feel like I am watching everyone from home get married and have kids. I’m so happy for them but I do wish I could watch this happening in person. 

5. Just being alone. Is Van life lonely, yes and no. But what gets me is how much emotional shit gets stirred up that you have to work through. The last 2.5 years have been the most mentally exhausting and rewarding years when it comes to working through some of the mental patterns I’ve been struggling with. 

But Quin… why are you doing van life…. Because at the end of the day, I LOVE it. If I got an apartment or house right now, I would stay there for two weeks and already want to leave. I love what van life allows me to do. I love the community in van life. I just love van life. 

But I did want to be honest and open and share MY van life cons and what I’ve been struggling with over the last few years.

How-to stay at a Fire Lookout in Washington👇🏻
 
Fire Lookouts are one of the coolest things (in my opinion) about hiking in Washington!
 
These fire lookouts were built in the 1900s after many fires devastated the area. Many were abandoned, but you can still experience 93 of them in Washington! (And some you can even work in for the summer!)
 
There are fire lookouts that you can:
	•	Sleep in at a first come first served basis for FREE.
	•	Pre-book to reserve
	•	Visit Only! Off Limits to sleep.
 
You can research where to find them on Washington tourism websites, alltrails, recreation.go v and various blogs.
 
First Come, First Served: if you are lucky enough to start your day early and snag a spot at the lookout, you CANNOT close the doors. You are more than welcome to drop your stuff & make yourself at home, but you still must allow access to the lookout for the public.
 
If you DON’T snag a first come, first served lookout, I always recommend bringing a tent as a backup plan.
 
Bathrooms: some actually DO have bathrooms (or privy’s) that are a bit of of a hike down from the lookout. But just in case, make sure to follow proper LNT rules for your waste— AKA bring a wag bag just in case!
 
What’s inside: It depends! Sometimes the lookouts have games, old gas for stoves, guest books, maps, lightning stools, sleeping bags & pillows. Each lookout is completely different!
 
Tip: Be careful of MICE! I recommend hanging your packs before you go to sleep to about any mouseys in your houseys.
 
And finally,  please remember to pack out what you pack in and leave no trace 💖

I normally HATE posts like this so let me give you some content👇🏻
 
Every person has their own special road life story and how they entered it and what they do for a living to maintain it… so here is mine:
 
After working as a marketing director and event producer for a magazine for seven years, I decided I needed a break and bought a van after a friend passed away in November 2020.
 
I WAS *happy* with my life…. but I wanted to take a chance on myself…. I wanted to experience something I had never experienced NOW because your days are not promised.
 
So, put my thirty days notice in, took my savings and I purchased an empty cargo van.
 
TBH, I didn’t really have a plan. I told myself I would budget out a few months and try to work freelance or get a seasonal job OR it would all fail and I would just go back to my old life and be happy that I tried it.
 
Now, as marketing professional, I had been using *the other video platform* as a research project. I posted videos about traveling solo as a woman, travel itineraries & how to take your cats on a hike and had gotten a minor following.
 
Three weeks after I quit my job, I got an email from Under Armor. They had seen some of my videos on the internet and wanted to work with me on a campaign… and then soon after, I started my own marketing company where I do photography/videography and marketing/social media consultations.
 
That was almost three years ago….
 
You have no idea what doors will open when you close one. In my opinion, my life started when I jumped out of my comfort zone and I am forever grateful.
 
Sidenote: I recognize my privilege in that I am VERY lucky to be doing this and many don't have the same story. Many can't just quit their jobs and live in a van.
 
But you can start to take small steps at doing what you want to do. Maybe its part time van life, maybe it’s starting a jewelry business, maybe it's being a photographer etc. Just START NOW. Because a year from now you will be so happy you did.

	•	Peace over drama & distance over disrespect
	•	I still learning to detach and that the only person/situation you can control is YOURSELF… so accept situations as they are and leave people as they are.

	•	Don’t feel shameful of your grief… FEEL IT & LET IT OUT.

How-To: Fly w/ Cats! Everything you need to know👇🏻
 
I have been travelling with cats for the last three years on planes, trains & automobiles, so here’s my advice on taking your cat on a plane!
 
Step 1: Carriers
	•	You’ll want to pick a carrier your cats are comfortable with/in. Atlas prefers an expandable backpack.
	•	A few weeks before the trip, put the carrier out so they can get comfortable around it. This helps them associate the carrier with *ALARM*
 
Step 2: Tote Bag of Goodies
	•	A collapsible litterbox
	•	Large pee pads
	•	A water holder
	•	Hydrating treats
	•	Collapsible food bowl
	•	PLENTLY of wipes
	•	PLENTY of zip block bags
	•	Litter
	•	Plastic gloves

(I got all of these products from @chewy & Amaz0n!)
 
Step 3: Medication
	•	Homeopet Anxiety Drops (they work OK)
	•	Ask your vet for Gabapentin (or like)
	•	Give you cats the medication the night before the flight & the morning of an hour before the airport! 
 
Step 4: Food/Bathroom
	•	A few hours before the flight take their food away
	•	Make sure they try to go to the bathroom before you leave
 
Airport
	•	Reserve an IN PET CABIN tag in advance online! This was $125 per flight.
 
Security
	•	You can ask for a PRIVATE SCREENING ROOM (takes a lot of time)
	•	OR walk your cat through the detector
 
Airplane:
	•	Isle Seat = quick access to bathroom for them
	•	Window = less interruptions of people walking by
	•	Bring a blanket/sweatshirt to cover their carrier so they can sleep
	•	If they can sleep or are loud- put the carrier on your lap!
 
LMK if you have any questions or tips to add!
 
GOOD LUCK!!!!!

Canada Bucketlist Spots:
 
1. Lake Moraine at Sunrise. Since this road is closed to personal vehicals, you’ll either have to take a shuttle or BIKE RIDE there! We rented bikes in Banff and rode up for sunrise!

2. Drive Icefields Parkway. This has to be the most beautiful road in North America. HANDS DOWN. Every turn is magical.

3. Rent a Canoe at Emerald Lake. Canoe rentals are MUCH CHEAPER here than some of the other popular locations. You can also take your pet with you (up to 50lbs!).

4. Spirit Island in Jasper National Park. You can’t hike here! Instead you can ONLY get here by canoe (28km row) or shuttle! We had a backcountry permit so we canoed AND camped!

5. Big Beehive Trail & Lake Agnes Tea House. This relatively short hike will get you to some of the best views over Lake Louise. On the way down, make sure to go to the Tea House. It’s INCREDIBLE and worth the wait if there is a line. Trust me. GO.

6. Lake Louise. Yes, this is a very popular place, but for good reason! You can hike, rent canoes and cold plunge!

Van Life & CATS: everything you need to know👇🏻

Hi, I’m Quin and I have been traveling solo in a van with my cats for over three years! After LOTS of trial & error… here are my favorite tips.

NOTHING is spon btw. 

LMK if you have any questions or any tips of your own to share! 

Trackers: 
I use two types of trackers depending on my location’s service. They do wear them both on a breakaway collar at the same time.
	• Bluetooth (for out of service): @tile 
	• GPS (for in service): @tractive 

Litterbox: 
	• I recommend an enclosed space next to your toilet to help contain smells! 
	• Small ventilation fan 
	• Doggy door (note.. Not all cats like this. Otto hated it & Atlas loved it) 
	• Charcoal deodorizer bags 
	• Small carpet or fake grass next to box to help w/ tracking 

Temperature Controls: 
	• Too Cold = I have a heater that runs off my gas tank
	• Too Hot = I have 2 fans & two windows that slide open. When these are turned on, they create an amazing wind tunnel.

Security: 
	• I used a @ring camera that connects to my wifi hot spot when I am gone. I only do this when I am in mostly city areas.

Collars, Harnesses, Leashes: 
	• ALWAYS get a breakaway collar just in case! 
	• Harnesses will be TRICKY for them. I will do a full video on this, but try multiple harnesses to see which one they tolerate the most. 
	• I recommend getting a retractable leash. So much easier! 

Backpacks: 
	• DO NOT get one of those cute plastic ones. They are dangerous. 
	• I recommend getting a soft, breathable one that your cat likes that also has enough support for your back!
